    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-04-03T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-04-03T12:00:00-05:00" n="296"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d296">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 Four Power Pact/21: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Italy</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Garrett</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rome</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-04-03T18:00:00+01:00"
                            >April 3, 1933—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received April 3—2:40 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>20. My 18, March 22, 10 a.m.<note n="27" xml:id="d296fn27">Not printed.</note>
                    The British Ambassador presented to the chief of the Italian Government this
                    afternoon a revised text of the proposed four power pact. He tells me that it
                    differs from the second text in two points, namely: <list>
                        <label>(1)</label>
                        <item>Any reference to a possible failure of the Disarmament Conference is
                            omitted.</item>
                        <pb facs="0505" n="403" xml:id="pg_403"/>
                        <label>(2)</label>
                        <item>Any power will be admitted at its request as an equal in any
                            discussions that may concern it.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>This third text has also been handed by Lord Tyrrell<note n="28"
                        xml:id="d296fn28">British Ambassador to France.</note> to the French
                    Government and Sir Ronald Graham believes will be transmitted to Berlin through
                    the Italian Ambassador there. Mussolini agreed to it in principle.</p>
                <p>Repeated to the American Embassy, Paris, for Norman Davis.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Garrett</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
